**Introduction**

Robotics is a rapidly advancing technological area whose popularity is growing, especially in a University environment. Drones are now becoming widely used with a large spectrum of applications. Unmanned land vehicles are also proving useful, both in commercial and experimental areas. One capability that is essential to these vehicles is the ability to navigate in an environment that has many dangers and obstacles. We provide a solution to this task, one that is low cost and simple enough to be implemented by a group of University students.

**Statement of Problem**

        One of the main prerequisites of a robust navigation system is reliable software for obstacle detection. It is desirable that this software operates efficiently in real time without any bottlenecks. There is a plethora of algorithms and libraries that have been built for this task that utilize different hardware sensors. But there is one drawback: many of these algorithms allow the vehicle to operate in limited environments, such as indoors or on the road with predefined paths. Can a vehicle have a simple ancillary system that can help it navigate autonomously in any environment? Another problem is the cost of cameras that are used. A LIDAR camera is used in some of the self-driving vehicles, and their costs can surpass $1000. Is there a sensor that can provide both sophistication and affordability so that it may be used for low cost projects involving fully autonomous vehicles?

**Solution**

One sensor that can be critical for the task of autonomous navigation is a depth camera. A depth camera beams out a predetermined light pattern and receives this pattern back, ultimately calculating 3-dimentional positions of points of the environment in its field of view. These groups of points are called a point cloud and they can be used for different tasks such as 3D scanning of objects and their recognition. In terms of navigation, this point cloud data can be used to first create a 3D surface model of the environment and possibly use it as a map. Algorithms can calculate which parts of the 3D model are structured to allow a vehicle to pass through or stand there, avoiding all obstacles in the meantime. The beauty of using a 3D map of the environment instead of 2D is that more complex types of environments, like hills and ramps, can be precisely represented (2D would only allow X and Y components of the position, while 3D can represent the Z component which is the height of the environment). I therefore propose to research and implement this methodology of 3D mapping with depth cameras for autonomous navigation.

**Implementation and Preliminary Testing**

        I have written software that implements and tests a portion of the proposed navigation system, specifically the part that divides the 3D map into accessible and inaccessible areas. One main problem that this algorithm must handle is the sheer size of the point cloud that needs to be processed. Point clouds do not represent an actual 3D model: we would need to do triangulation of these point to create the model (Figure 1). Triangulation will represent the surfaces of the environment correctly but there will also be noise and redundant data; the number of triangles can be more than half a million, which will take a lot of computational power. Additionally, raw triangles are not the best data type to use in algorithms as groups of them will all face considerably different directions. The algorithm that I provide alleviates this issue by simplifying the 3D model without jeopardizing the general shape of the surface. This algorithm also simplifies the whole model by making it discrete: this significantly simplifies data management. Results of the preliminary software can be seen in Figure 2; they show that it is indeed possible to create a functional 3D map with the use of a Depth Camera.

        Further work needs to be done on this software and this is what our research can focus on. The raw point cloud data can be filtered and averaged to remove parts that are unnecessary. For path finding, anything rudimentary such as an A\* algorithm could be implemented. For this to happen, the accessible areas would have to be divided into distinct regions (an example in Figure 2 would be the curved ramp path delimited with yellow lines). A more global representation of the environment will have to be in place in the latter stages of the software design, one that will combine current 3D meshes into a larger map. These tasks can all be accomplished but the focus will be stronger and optimized mathematical algorithms that will make the results even more precise and reliable.

**Requirements and Costs**

        Several depth cameras exist that can be interfaced to our software. I have already used the Microsoft Kinect 2.0 camera and it has worked fine at ranges of less than 8 meters. This camera is 3 years old and as far as the newer depth cameras go, Intel&#39;s D400 series cameras seem to be the perfect choice. Priced at less than $200, this camera has thrice the frame rate, almost 4 times the resolution, farther range, and better point cloud generation in its hardware (&quot;Intel® RealSense™ Depth Camera&quot;, n.d.). What makes this camera a superb choice for this navigation system is that unlike Kinect, this camera was designed with robotics navigation in mind. Another essential component to our system would be a small laptop computer or Microcontrollers that have USB 3.0 support. An example would be the Intel&#39;s Atom single board computers, whose cost is less than $200 for different models. Lastly, to be able to test our system in a real environment, we would need to have a small vehicle that can support the camera and the computers. A large RC car can accomplish this task. Special vehicles exist for robotic tasks in mind, but their price is unaffordable.

**Conclusion**

**       ** Autonomous navigation opens doors to countless possibilities. Military and civilian tasks that center on search and rescue can now be done without putting human lives at risks. In situations where human control is problematic, such as space travel with its latencies of communication, autonomous navigation can help rovers explore an environment and gather useful information. Our proposed software and hardware system can make this task a possibility, one that comes at an affordable cost as well as ease of implementation for University students.
